<font color="#FF0000">I SHOULD HAVE JOINED THE ARMY!</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jul 10 12:08:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Boy! Sure did touch a few buttons. Okay,<br>
 I agree everyone of you has every perfect right to be wrong  : - )<br><br>
To Doc Del, (and Joe),  This is the entry I had written down in the diary I kept in nam. It might have been 1st Cal, but I had recorded it as 1st Cal. I'll don't have the after-action reports for that time. It was Operation Rock March 06-10, 1968. Maybe Joe the Historian and writer can tell us. <br><br>
March 10, 1968<br>
Early the morning of the 10th we moved out and entered a thick forest. There were scattered clearing in between so the squads in our platoon started leap frogging over the open areas until we came to a series of ridges. Shortly before noon while we were moving out through an open area, we were hit from one of the ridges. We were pinned down out and out in the open. 2nd platoon soon came up behind us open up and a fierce firefight ensued.<br>
The entrenched enemy had opened up while we were in the cleft of a small valley between two small ridges. Soon the rest of the Company had moved up and were returning fire over our heads. <br>
A few minutes later the enemies' fire shifted and they were engaged by one of the supporting Companies that had been walking our left flank.  From then on, we were engaging them as they and we moved from ridge to ridge. The off and on again firefights would last a few minutes before contact was broken and we moved on.<br>
Finally we had them on the run, but lost them as they moved through a narrow trail in a dense forest area.<br><br>
By early afternoon, we had reached our objective, a knoll at one end of a series of mountain ridges.  The platoon crossed over, more like crawled over the little knoll. When we came out on the other side crawling, dirty, hungry and scared. We could see a beautiful green valley below. I moved my gun team further up the edge while we waited for the rest of the company behind us to catch up. <br>
When we looked down on the valley below, we could not believe what we were seeing. <br>
Smack in the middle of the open fields of the valley below. The US 1st Air Calvary was marching in formation. They were walking around singing, with their rifles slung over their shoulders, diddy-bopping as if they were out for a Sunday picnic. Trucks, tanks, and armored personal carriers all of them making such a racket the whole valley trembled. A number of gunships and medevac helicopters with the Red Cross insignia boldly stamped on their nose flew overhead. A new type of helicopter, slick like the face of a cobra shot through the valley at breath taking speed, others followed behind.<br>
 We could not believe our eyes. <br>
&quot;Don't those guys know that there's a war going on,&quot; I said to James. He sat there dumbfounded, eyes wide open. <br>
 &quot;I should have joined the Army,&quot; he said. <br><br>
We could hear the army below laughing, joking, and walking as if they had no idea that a real war was going on. Ice-cream soldiers is what we called them, and now I knew why. We had been fighting and dodging bullets and been out up to our necks in filth and dirt for days and here these soldiers were walking around as if nothing was going on. They all had clean new camouflaged fatigues on.  They were walking in formation with their rifles swung over their shoulders. What a way to fight the war. It was times like this that like James I wished that I had joined the Army as well. Later that day we were helilifted out and dropped off at battalion HQ's. The operation was over.<br><br>
No disrespect meant, just what an 19 year old Marine had written down in his diary 30 years ago.<br><br>
That's all right I believe 
